Thomas Ernest Hare (March 16, 1883 – March 9, 1939) was an American singer who recorded prolifically during the 1920s and 1930s, finding fame as a radio star on the Happiness Boys radio program.
He was Al Jolson's understudy in the Broadway musical Sinbad during 1919–20.
He made a series recordings with Al Bernard in the late 1910s and the start of the 1920s.
He made a series recordings with Al Bernard in the late 1910s and the start of the 1920s.
After he met Billy Jones in 1919, they teamed in 1920 when Brunswick executive Gus Haenschen had them sing an accompaniment on a Brunswick recording.

Similarities between the two singers were often noted: same height, same weight, and birthdays a few days apart.
They began on radio October 18, 1921 on WJZ in Newark, New Jersey.
Sponsored by Happiness Candy, they were heard as the Happiness Boys beginning August 22, 1923 on New York's WEAF, moving to NBC for a run from 1926–1929.

By 1928, they were the highest-paid singers in radio, earning $1,250 a week.

After Hare's death in 1939 of bronchopneumonia, Jones continued to perform, teaming in 1939–40 with Hare's 16-year-old daughter, Marilyn Hare (1923–1981).
